<Base title="Knowledge platform — Andrew Yang">
  <h1>A 1,477-repository platform with one operator</h1>
  <p class="lede">
    My reading notes, handbooks, and topic sites live in 1,477 repositories under
    one GitHub organization. At that scale, "personal websites" becomes a fleet
    management problem — which is exactly why it's here.
  </p>

  <h2>The engineering underneath</h2>
  <ul class="clean">
    <li>
      <strong>Fleet governance:</strong> a Gradle convention plugin published to a
      package registry pins toolchain and formatting for every repository; a shared
      Renovate preset rolls dependency updates across the fleet monthly with automerge.
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>Provisioning pipeline:</strong> a Kotlin CLI takes a queue of books and
      creates repositories end-to-end — AI-assisted metadata, duplicate detection
      against a cached repo index, template instantiation, cover processing, docs
      scaffolding, and GitHub Pages activation.
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>Metadata discipline:</strong> a three-tier topic taxonomy with a
      whitelist keeps 1,400+ repositories queryable; idempotent provisioning makes
      re-runs safe.
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>Operational scar tissue:</strong> batch pushes hitting Pages deploy
      throttling, formatting hooks across ~1,300 working copies, wrapper upgrades
      across generations of JDKs — fleet problems, fleet solutions.
    </li>
  </ul>

  <h2>v1 → v2 of the same idea</h2>
  <p>
    The provisioning CLI is a file-based queue with a two-phase AI workflow — an
    async content pipeline, version one. <a href="/demo/">ai-radar</a> is version
    two of the same problem with production-grade semantics: a real broker,
    delivery guarantees, retry topology, and observability.
  </p>
</Base>
